data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Must replace with cooperative cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Removed** | No equivalent needed |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never thrown** | Dead code — remove |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state by unwinding the stack at arbitrary points. .NET 8 enforces **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original Thread.Join(timeout) did
            task.Wait(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }

        // Task.Result re-throws as AggregateException, preserving original behavior
        return task.Result;
    }

    // Async-first overload (preferred in modern .NET)
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative — the work must observe the token:**
```csharp
// ❌ Will NOT stop on timeout — ignores the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(_ => SlowUninterruptibleWork(), timeout);

// ✅ Checks the token periodically
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, timeout);
```

**2. If you wrap code you don't control**, the task may keep running after timeout. Mitigate with a fire-and-forget pattern:
```csharp
// For uncooperative 3rd-party code that can't check a token
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithHardTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);
    var completed = await Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(timeout));

    if (completed != task)
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        // ⚠️ The task is still running — there's no safe way to kill it

    return await task; // Unwraps exceptions
}
```

**3. Don't catch `ThreadAbortException`** — it no longer exists. Any `catch (ThreadAbortException)` is dead code and should be removed.

**4. `Task.Result` wraps in `AggregateException`** just like the original code did manually. If you prefer unwrapped exceptions, use `await` (the async overload) instead.

### Migration Checklist

- Replace `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource`
- Remove `Thread.ResetAbort()` and `ThreadAbortException` handling
- Add `CancellationToken` parameter to `Func<T>` signature
- Update all callers to accept and observe the token
- Prefer the `async` overload for new code paths
